quote.text:
The crypto privacy game has changed.

Soon, projects will no longer compete on pure privacy tech! Monero and Zcash will compete on culture and adoption.

Bold prediction, I know, but I believe it for a number of reasons.

1‚É£ Full-chain membership proofs level the tech playing field

For the entirety of its existence up until now, Zcash had the significant technological advantage over just about every single different privacy-focused cryptocurrency, including Monero.

Every couple of years over the past decade, a major shortcoming in Monero's model was discovered, then fixed. But compared to the zero-knowledge approach, the leaks were just too many.

Very soon, however, full-chain membership proofs will be implemented in Monero, dramatically increasing the anonymity set. Practically speaking, this will mean much less privacy difference between Monero and Zcash at the base tech level.

2‚É£ Just about every project is exploring some type of privacy

The number of projects implementing some kind of advanced privacy function continues to grow. Too many to name.

Thanks to smart contracts, every programmatic chain can implement something like Railgun and enjoy top-level ZK privacy for anyone who runs the contract. Why would someone, say, swap ETH for ZEC to try to break the trail before they do some major swap, if they could just use Railgun and stay fully-private on ETH?

Even PayPal is implementing the equivalent of Confidential Transactions (transaction amounts are hidden), something proposed in Bitcoin a decade ago that never made it there.

Before, you could only use a couple of chains to remain private. Soon, you'll be able to use almost any one.

3‚É£ Privacy projects will compete on other metrics

Now, privacy-focused projects will have to compete on other things, like cost, ease of use, ecosystem, culture, regulatory status, etc.

This is where Zcash and Monero will continue to diverge even more.

Zcash is on more major exchanges, has better transparency tools, has better high-level partnerships (i.e. Brave), and has a significantly more "normie-friendly" message and brand. It's focusing on other features in the future such as staking, encrypted messages, tokens, and more.

Monero has much more adoption in the darknet and generally no-KYC world, a much stronger brand identity towards uncompromising privacy and cypherpunk values, and a much simpler UX for its privacy feature (don't have to worry, it's always on).

üèÖWHO WILL WIN THE PRIVACY COIN BATTLE?üèÖ

Short answer: I don't know.

So far, it looks like Monero's the clear winner. Overwhelming, even. Better than anyone in the privacy space, they've focused on their core product and messaging, and successfully gotten more actual users.
A real marketing machine!

Zcash has struggled to get meaningful usage (maybe the wallets issue from the sandblasting attack is to blame?). But some of the more mainstream partnerships, including Flexa and Brave, could make it a much safer option for regular people to use private crypto.

And who knows... maybe the whole push to appeal to the hardcores could put Monero in a position of being blacklisted, while less "spicy" cryptos like Zcash are still okay to use. Who knows?

Gun to my head üë®‚Äçü¶±üî´ I'd probably pick Monero out of the two to win out, because it already proved its ability to succeed. But really, could go to Zcash.

Either way, I'm happy to see both (and any/every privacy project) succeed. We're in so much better of a position in regards to financial privacy today than we were just a few years ago!

quote.text:
I'm leaving @FOUNDATIONdvcs and joining @cake

It's time for a new chapter in my journey building freedom tech, and I'm thrilled to announce that I'll be jumping in to help @vikrantnyc run Cake as VP of Operations starting in September.

Why Cake?

I've known Vik for many years in the space, and have been watching from the sidelines as he's worked hard to bring together an amazing team to build out a wallet that prioritizes ease-of-use and powerful privacy no matter what cryptocurrency people prefer. That all started with being the first Monero wallet on iOS, and has rapidly grown to being a cross-platform, multi-cryptocurrency wallet used by hundreds of thousands of people around the world.

The best part? @cakewallet has been paving the way in the privacy space for many years, including the latest push to be the first mobile wallet to include Silent Payments for Bitcoin and MWEB for Litecoin. My vision for Cake is to carry this privacy-first vision even further, continuing to push the envelope and let users access powerful privacy features with an intuitive, beautiful user experience that makes privacy easy.

The first three objectives I have will be improving and expanding Silent Payments support (especially improving the sync experience!), building out an amazing Lightning experience using the @Breez_Tech SDK, and fine-tuning and improving the existing Cake Wallet that you all know and love across the board.

I can't wait to step into this larger role, especially with friends that I've already gotten the chance to meet and get to know over the years. I'm also thrilled to be able to dedicate a bit more time to expanding access and ease-of-use for Monero, especially in the wake of the takedown of Samourai Wallet and the broad attacks against Bitcoin privacy.

Monero is a more important tool than ever, and Cake has been a key part of making Monero more useful over the years.

Grateful for Foundation

I have nothing but amazing things to say about @FOUNDATIONdvcs and the incredible people I've gotten to work with so closely over the past two years. We've gotten the chance to build the best Bitcoin hardware wallet out there in Passport, and turn Envoy from a simple companion app for Passport to a powerful standalone mobile wallet with the best coin control in the space.

I especially wanted to shout out @zachherbert and @btcqna, as they have been close friends and allies, giving me the chance to get started in the space and grow into what became a much larger role than originally planned with Foundation. Zach has gone above and beyond to empower me over the past two years, and his tireless efforts to drive Foundation forward and ensure we ship the best possible products has been inspiring.

@btcqna is the reason I'm even in Bitcoin in the first place, and was the key voice of reason that helped me understand the how and why of privacy in Bitcoin, as well as the power (and necessity) of going no-KYC-only. We've built a great friendship over the past two years and I'm honored to be able to have learned so much from him.

This has to be the most bittersweet move of my life, but I'm thrilled with the new prospects at Cake and know that those taking over in my place at Foundation are going to bring a unique approach to help them take the next step forward as well.

Now let's get back to building ü´°

P.S. - Keep an eye out, Cake and Foundation will be working closely together in the near future üëÄ
